  <article>

    <p class="opening">
      Our school's trash bin used to have three labels — biodegradable, non-biodegradable, recyclable — and exactly one destination, the same dump truck. Nobody checked. That contradiction is where this started for me, long before I understood words like "carbon footprint" or "climate resilience." I just knew the labels were lying, and sixteen-year-old me found that unreasonably annoying.
    </p>

    <section class="entry" id="e1">
      <div class="entry-head">
        <span class="entry-num">01</span>
        <h2>The trash bin that started it</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        I joined my school's Youth for Environment in Schools Organization, or YES-O, mostly because a friend needed one more member to complete their chapter's roster. I stayed because the first activity we ran was a genuinely embarrassing waste audit — we opened three days' worth of canteen trash in front of the whole junior high, sorted it by hand, and read out loud how much of the "biodegradable" bin was actually plastic straws and foil.
      </p>
      <p>
        Nobody clapped. A few people gagged. But that was the first time I understood that most environmental problems in a school aren't caused by a lack of rules — Lucena City actually has decent waste ordinances — they're caused by nobody being assigned to notice when the rules quietly stop being followed. YES-O, at least in our chapter, became the group that noticed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="entry" id="e2">
      <div class="entry-head">
        <span class="entry-num">02</span>
        <h2>What YES-O actually taught me</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        DepEd markets YES-O as a leadership and values-formation program, and on paper that's accurate but also kind of undersells it. What it actually taught me was closer to project management with soil under your fingernails — how to requisition seedlings from the City Environment and Natural Resources Office, how to keep a tree-planting log that a barangay official will actually sign, how to convince twenty distracted fifteen-year-olds to finish digging a hole in the sun without a single one of them quitting halfway.
      </p>
      <p>
        It also taught me that environmental work is unglamorous by design. Coastal or mangrove cleanups look good in a photo for maybe the first ten minutes. After that it's just repetitive, itchy, unfilmed labor — and that's precisely the part where you find out who actually cares versus who came for the certificate.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        The rehabilitation isn't the tree you plant today. It's whoever waters it in April, when there's no camera and no adviser watching.
        <span>— a note I wrote in our chapter logbook, Grade 10</span>
      </blockquote>
    </section>

    <div class="divider">◆</div>

    <section class="entry" id="e3">
      <div class="entry-head">
        <span class="entry-num">03</span>
        <h2>The Typhoon of Problems We Created</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        A typhoon is more than a weather event. It is the face of every environmental problem we've ignored for decades. Each storm carries not only wind and rain, but the consequences of deforestation, polluted waterways, poorly planned cities, and a warming climate. What crashes into our homes isn't just nature's fury—it is the accumulated weight of human neglect returning to demand its price.
      </p>
      <p>
        Growing up in Quezon Province, I have learned that environmental issues are never distant headlines. Every rainy season, familiar streets disappear beneath muddy water, rivers rise more quickly than before, and communities prepare for another cycle of rebuilding. These experiences shaped the way I view environmental responsibility—not as an optional advocacy, but as a necessity.
      </p>
      <p>
        As both an observer and someone who once served as the Chairperson of the Environmental Issue and Research Committee at Quezon National High School, I have had the opportunity to witness these challenges from two perspectives. I have seen how environmental degradation affects communities firsthand, but I have also studied the patterns behind these disasters—how climate change, unsustainable practices, and the loss of natural ecosystems continue to amplify their impact. That experience taught me that the environmental crisis is not a series of isolated events but a connected system of problems that demand informed, collective action.
      </p>
      <p>
        That understanding is what led me to continue my advocacy as a member of the Youth for Environment in Schools Organization (YES-O). Joining YES-O was not simply about participating in school activities; it was about transforming observation into action. Whether through environmental education, community initiatives, or promoting sustainable practices, I came to realize that meaningful change begins long before a typhoon makes landfall. While we cannot stop every storm from coming, we can address the environmental conditions that make each one more destructive than the last.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="cta" id="join">
      <span class="label">Call to action · 01</span>
      <h3>Tara, walk into your school's YES-O room this week</h3>
      <p>You don't need a title or a green thumb. Most chapters run on whoever actually shows up on cleanup day — that's the entire application process.</p>
