    <section class="entry" id="e4">
      <div class="entry-head">
        <span class="entry-num">04</span>
        <h2>Where youth environmentalism falls short</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        I want to be honest about the limits of this, because I think a lot of youth-led sustainability content oversells itself. Tree-planting activities that never get a survival-rate follow-up plant a lot of trees that quietly die in month three. Ordinances get passed at the barangay level and then never get enforced because nobody was assigned enforcement in the first place. And frankly, a good number of our own activities were designed around what would look complete in an accomplishment report, not around what the actual ecosystem needed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Youth organizations like YES-O also can't substitute for the structural stuff — proper drainage systems, enforced coastal setbacks, waste management budgets that survive a change in local administration. What we can do is smaller, but I'd argue it still matters — we can keep the pressure visible, keep the follow-up happening, and refuse to let "we did an activity" stand in for "the problem is handled."
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="divider">◆</div>

    <section class="entry" id="e5">
      <div class="entry-head">
        <span class="entry-num">05</span>
        <h2>Small roots, planted on purpose</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        Today, my environmental advocacy no longer needs a stage or a certificate to feel worth doing. I bring my own bag when I buy pasalubong, I've gotten mildly insufferable about correcting people who trash-mix at school events, and I still check on the seedlings from our first planting whenever I pass that stretch of road. None of it is dramatic. All of it is the difference between doing something and having done something once.
      </p>
      <p>
        If there's one thing three years of this has actually changed in me, it's that I stopped needing a typhoon to remind me why it matters. The bill Quezon pays every rainy season isn't an argument I need to win anymore — it's just the reason I show up to the trash audit, the mangrove cleanup, the follow-up watering schedule that nobody else volunteered for. Growing up green here was never optional. I just decided to do it on purpose instead of by accident.
      </p>
    </section>

